The last theorem of Fermat is a mathematical conjecture that states that there is no positive integer n such that x^n + y^n = z^n, where x, y, and z are all non-zero integers. The conjecture was made by Pierre de Fermat in 1637, but it remained unproven for over three centuries. In 1994, Andrew Wiles proved the theorem using advanced techniques in mathematics.

The last theorem of Fermat is a fundamental problem in number theory and has been studied for centuries. It is one of the most difficult unsolved problems in mathematics and is considered to be one of the most important open problems in mathematics. It is a symbol of human ingenuity and creativity and is a testament to the power of human intelligence.

The theorem is named after Pierre de Fermat, who first stated it as a conjecture in 1637. He wrote that he had found a proof that was too long to fit on the margin of a page of his book. This led to the conjecture being known as Fermat's last theorem.

Fermat's last theorem states that there are no solutions to the equation x^n + y^n = z^n for any positive integers n, x, y, and z. The conjecture has been tested for all small values of n and it has been shown that there are no solutions for any value of n less than 400000. However, no one has been able to prove it for higher values of n.

In 1978, Ken Ribet proved that if the conjecture were false then there would be an integer m such that m was prime and m^2 + 4 was also prime. This led to the development of an "attack" strategy for proving the theorem which involved finding all possible primes p such that p^2 + 4 is also prime. In 1993, Gerhard Frey announced a new approach to this strategy which led to new progress in proving the theorem.

In 1993, Andrew Wiles published his proof of Fermat's last theorem in "Annals of Mathematics". This proof used sophisticated methods in algebraic number theory which were developed by Pierre de Fermat himself more than three centuries earlier. The proof relied heavily on the work of other mathematicians such as Jacobi, Legendre, Eisenstein and Hecke. It was hailed as one of the most important mathematical achievements in recent history and won Wiles the Fields Medal in 1994.

Since then, other mathematicians have attempted to prove Fermat's last theorem using different methods but none have been successful so far. It remains one of the most important open problems in mathematics and continues to inspire mathematicians around the world.

